ACT ΙΙΙ.

Scene I. Interior of Epignomus’ house. His slave Stichus, his female musicians and probably his parasites and others, are on the stage. Epignomus enters from the back of the house, returns thanks to his gods, and announces that his good fortune has reconciled him to his father-in-law. Then Stichus asks for a holiday, which he gets, and declares his intention of having a dinner with his friend Sagarinus and their common friend Stephanium.

Scene II. Street outside Epignomus² house. Enter Gelasi- mus in quest of a meal, to try his luck with Epignomus. To him enters Epignomus from the central door. The scene is occupied with the parasite’s ineffectual efforts to secure an invitation.
